{"key":"post-12784475","value":"<?xml version=\"1.0\"?>\n<post>\n<id>12784475</id>\n<content>&lt;/font&gt;&lt;blockquote&gt;&lt;font class=&quot;small&quot;&gt;Quote:&lt;/font&gt;&lt;hr /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;b&gt;&lt;i&gt;iFung said:&lt;/i&gt;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;br /&gt;If the lowest setting on my oven is 150, can I put my pot of water/substrate in there at 150 for a while to pasteurize it instead of manually trying to keep it in range on the stove top?&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;hr /&gt;&lt;/blockquote&gt;&lt;font class=&quot;post&quot;&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;It might take ten to fifteen hours in the oven at 150F for the water and substrate to reach that temperature, since air is such a crappy heat transfer medium.&amp;nbsp; &lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Or, a few minutes on a stove top.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Look at it this way:&amp;nbsp; It takes 90 minutes with the oven turned up to 350F for a small chicken to reach 170F, which is when a chicken is considered cooked.&amp;nbsp; I'm assuming your pot of water is much larger than a chicken.&amp;nbsp; You'll be far better off to stick to tried and true pasteurization methods.&amp;nbsp; You want to heat your substrates rapidly to 140F and then keep them there for an hour to 90 minutes, and then cool them off to use.&amp;nbsp; This process would take many hours in the oven, screwing up the pasteurization.&lt;br /&gt;RR</content>\n<name>RogerRabbit</name>\n<next></next>\n<prev>12784435</prev>\n<first>12784038</first>\n<last>12784475</last>\n<when>1277232566</when>\n<utime>06/22/10 09:49 PM</utime>\n</post>"}